+---
+title: Execution patterns
+description: How queue-level execution patterns (static-dag, pipeline, map-reduce) layer above the engine tick — including the extendRun seam, run.extended audit events, the gate/respawn circle-back, and the forward-arc-never-rewind invariant.
+---
+
+The core engine described in [How an offload run executes](/agora/explanation/how-offload-runs/)
+is deliberately simple: a DAG of WorkItems, a dependency resolver, and a
+fire-and-reconcile tick loop. Execution patterns are a **strategy layer above that
+engine** — they inspect terminal items after each tick and may append new items to
+a live run. Nothing inside the engine changes; the pattern phase is a hook that runs
+between the engine tick and the seal check.
+
+This page explains what patterns are, how to attach one to a queue, the mechanics of
+the `extendRun` seam and the `run.extended` audit event, how the pipeline gate
+circle-back works, and why the forward-arc-never-rewind invariant is the guarantee
+that keeps dynamically-grown graphs acyclic and auditable.
+
+## What an execution pattern is
+
+A pattern is a **pure, stateless function** associated with a queue. After every
+engine tick, the orchestrator calls each pattern with a view of the terminal items
+produced so far on that queue's unsealed runs. The pattern inspects those items and
+returns — or returns nothing. If it returns items, those are **spawns**: new
+WorkItems to be appended to the run.
+
+Three built-in patterns ship with `agora-orchestrator`:
+
+- **`static-dag`** — the default no-op. No items are ever spawned; the run is
+  exactly what was submitted. Use this (or omit `pattern`) when the full graph is
+  known at submit time.
+- **`pipeline`** — drives a linear sequence of named stages. After each stage's
+  gate item reaches `done`, the pattern emits the next stage's items. It also
+  handles the **respawn circle-back**: if a gate item fails and the pattern decides
+  a retry makes sense (e.g. a lint gate, a quality check), it emits a fresh lineage
+  of fix-and-retry items appended to the same run.
+- **`map-reduce`** — a splitter item writes a list of targets to `outputs/`; the
+  pattern reads that manifest when the splitter reaches `done` and emits one
+  `map` WorkItem per target, then emits a single `reduce` item that `depends_on`
+  all of them. The number of map items is unknown at submit time.
+
+Patterns are pure: they read item state, they never write it directly, and they keep
+no mutable variables between calls. Spawn ids are **deterministic** given the items
+that triggered them, which matters for crash-recovery (below).
+
+## Queue-level pattern config
+
+Patterns are configured **per queue** in `agora.config.ts` (or `agora.config.js`),
+not per run. This means every run placed on a `pipeline` queue is governed by the
+pipeline pattern; you do not opt individual runs in or out.
+
+```ts
+// agora.config.ts
+export default defineConfig({
+  orchestrator: {
+    queues: [
+      {
+        name: 'default',
+        concurrency: 4,
+        // no pattern — static-dag behaviour
+      },
+      {
+        name: 'pipeline',
+        concurrency: 1,
+        pattern: {
+          type: 'pipeline',
+          stages: ['lint', 'test', 'deploy'],
+          maxGateRetries: 2,
+        },
+      },
+      {
+        name: 'fanout',
+        concurrency: 8,
+        pattern: {
+          type: 'map-reduce',
+          splitter: 'split',
+          reducer:  'aggregate',
+        },
+      },
+    ],
+  },
+});
+```
+
+The pattern object is validated at startup, not at submit time. Submitting a run to a
+pattern-bound queue requires only that the run include the items the pattern expects
+as anchors (e.g. a `split` item for `map-reduce`, or a stage-gate item for
+`pipeline`); the dynamically spawned items are the pattern's responsibility, not the
+submitter's.
+
+## The extendRun seam and run.extended audit events
+
+When a pattern returns spawns, the orchestrator applies them through the **`extendRun`
+seam** — the single code path through which any dynamic growth of a run is allowed.
+`extendRun` does three things before the tick resumes:
+
+1. **Validates** the merged graph — the existing items plus the proposed spawns — with
+   the same `validateRun` logic used at submit time. Cycles, missing `depends_on`
+   targets, and schema violations all reject the whole spawn batch, not just the
+   offending item.
+2. **Attributes** the spawn to the actor `pattern:<queueName>` (e.g.
+   `pattern:pipeline`), so the audit trail distinguishes human submits from
+   machine-driven growth.
+3. **Records** a `run.extended` audit event for each spawned item, naming the
+   **cause item** — the terminal item whose completion triggered the spawn. The event
+   carries the full item spec, so the audit bundle is self-contained: a reviewer can
+   reconstruct the run's growth without access to the live queue config.
+
+Because `extendRun` runs **before the tick's seal check**, a run that just grew
+structurally cannot be sealed that tick. Sealing requires every item to be terminal;
+newly spawned items start as `pending`, so the run stays unsealed until the next
+tick's reconcile cycle catches up. This ordering is intentional: it prevents a
+pattern and the seal from racing.
+
+## The gate/respawn circle-back
+
+The pipeline pattern's most non-obvious behaviour is the **gate/respawn
+circle-back**: a mechanism that lets a failed gate trigger a fresh fix attempt on the
+*same run*, rather than failing the run outright.
+
+A pipeline gate is an ordinary WorkItem whose role is to check the result of the
+preceding stage. If the gate's executor exits non-zero, the engine marks it `failed`
+in the normal way — its `depends_on` dependents skip-cascade and the run heads
+toward settled. But before settlement, the pattern phase fires. The pipeline pattern
+sees a `failed` gate with `gateRetries < maxGateRetries`, and instead of doing
+nothing, it emits a **respawn group**: a fresh set of fix-and-retry items with new
+ids, where the new gate item `depends_on` the new fix items, and the new fix items
+`depends_on` the original (failed) gate. Because those `depends_on` edges point
+*backward* at already-terminal items, the new items are immediately `ready` after
+`extendRun` inserts them. The failed branch — the original gate item and whatever
+led to it — is untouched: it stays `failed` in the history.
+
+The circle-back is not literally a cycle in the graph. It is new nodes appended
+downstream of a failed terminal node. The original gate's failure is sealed history;
+the new attempt is a new lineage. The run graph remains a DAG throughout.
+
+## The forward-arc-never-rewind invariant
+
+Every spawn that any pattern is allowed to produce must satisfy one rule:
+**all `depends_on` edges in the spawned items point to items that already exist in
+the run at spawn time.**
+
+Formally: if `extendRun` is called at time *t*, every id in every spawned item's
+`depends_on` must be present in the run's item set as it existed at time *t* (before
+the spawn is applied). The validation step in `extendRun` enforces this; a spawn that
+references a not-yet-existing item id is rejected.
+
+This invariant has three consequences:
+
+**The graph is acyclic by construction.** New items can only depend on older items.
+There is no way to introduce a cycle through `extendRun`, because a cycle would
+require at least one edge pointing forward — to an item not yet in the run at spawn
+time — which is precisely what the invariant prohibits.
+
+**Replay is safe.** Because patterns are pure and spawn ids are deterministic, a
+pattern that is called twice on the same terminal-item state produces the same spawn
+batch. `extendRun` skips already-present ids, so a crash between the pattern call and
+the `run.extended` audit write produces a no-op on restart. The orchestrator
+re-derives the spawn directive, finds all ids already present, and continues. No
+dedup table, no idempotency key — the invariant plus deterministic ids provide it for
+free.
+
+**Provenance closure holds for dynamically grown runs.** The `agora verify` command
+checks that every input consumed by every item is traceable to an upstream item's
+output in the same run. Spawned items enter the run through `extendRun` the same way
+original items enter through `submitRun`; they carry the same `needs` fields and
+produce the same `resultRef` artifacts. The verifier sees no difference between a
+statically submitted item and a dynamically spawned one — closure is verified over
+the full item set, however it grew, with no special case for patterns.
+
+Together these three properties mean that a run governed by a pattern — however many
+times it circles back, however many map items the splitter produces — remains as
+auditable and verifiable as a fully static DAG submitted in one shot.
